'''Kamal el-Fayoumi''' ({{lang-ar|ÙÙ Ø§Ù Ø§ÙÙÙÙÙ Ù}}, {{IPA-arz|kÃ¦ËmÃ¦Ël elfÃ¦jËjuËmi|IPA}}) is an [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] [[socialist]] and [[workers' rights]] activist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/en/node/158188 |title=Hundreds of protesters stage anti-Mubarak rally in downtown Cairo |author=John Ehab |publisher=Al-Masry Al-Youm |date=2010-09-21 |accessdate=2011-05-05 }}</ref> He is a member of the [[Workers Democratic Party]].<ref name=alive>{{cite web |url=http://mrzine.monthlyreview.org/2011/hanna020511.html |title=Egypt's Workers Keep the Revolution Alive |author=Simon Hanna |publisher=MRZine |date=2010-05-02 |accessdate=2011-05-24 }}</ref> He is possibly{{vague|date=October 2011}} best known for his role as one of the leaders of the [[2008 Egyptian general strike|Egyptian general strike]] in 2008,<ref name=working>{{cite news |title=A working class hero |author=[[Hossam el-Hamalawy]] |url=http://www.arabawy.org/2009/11/18/fayoum/ |publisher=3arabawy |date=2009-12-18 |accessdate=2011-05-04 }}</ref> when three strike leaders were arrested following anti-[[Hosni Mubarak|Mubarak]] regime riots. The three were later released from detention and given back their jobs, which was seen as a key victory for the [[El-Mahalla El-Kubra]] textile workers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Egyptian strike leaders are released |url=http://www.socialistworker.co.uk/art.php?id=15149 |publisher=Socialist Worker |date=2008-07-14 |accessdate=2011-05-24 }}</ref> Socialist and blogger [[Hossam el-Hamalawy]] called el-Fayoumi a "[[Proletariat|working class]] hero".<ref name=working/> El-Fayoumi also participated in the [[2011 Egyptian revolution|Egyptian revolution]] in 2011 as one of the leaders of workers who went on strike.<ref>{{cite news |title=Egypt's Mahalla workers strike, bring demands to the military |author=Marwa Hussein |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/3/12/5777/Business/Economy/Egypts-Mahalla-workers-strike,-bring-demands-to-th.aspx |publisher=Ahram Online |date=2008-02-16 |accessdate=2011-05-24 }}</ref> After Mubarak's departure as [[President of Egypt|President]], el-Fayoumi declared: "All of us, as workers, said that the revolution began on February 11 when Mubarak left. When the head of the old regime stepped down, it was just the start of the revolution."<ref name=alive/>
